<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-450-082  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 450 082.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>IEEE Network  July 1989 v3 n4 p10(6).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Broadband communications: the commercial impact.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Timms, Stephen.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Broadband communications services based on optical fiber havealready appeared, but switched broadband services that requirereplacement of existing copper lines with optical fiber are onlybeginning to appear in commercial applications.andP;  It is predictedthat over 3 million US business sites and 2 million homes will beequipped with fiber access by the year 2000, with switchedservices becoming widespread by the mid 1990s.andP;  The infrastructurefor such broadband fiber services is already being set up in theUS, UK, West Germany, and France.andP;  Future growth is being drivenby market demand and investment interest.andP;  The three major earlyapplications for broadband will be high-speed data communication,backbone networks for LANs, and video conferencing.andP;  Futuregrowth, applications, and the use of optical fiber as a medium arealso described.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     TrendsFiber OpticsBroadbandSystem DevelopmentMarket AnalysisImpact AnalysisOutlook.andO;Feature:   illustrationchartgraph.andO;Caption:   Broadband services will address new application areas. (chart)The development timetable for broadband. (chart)Proportion of business sites with IBA and broadband applications.andO;(graph)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>